impl Solution {
    pub fn poor_pigs(buckets: i32, minutes_to_die: i32, minutes_to_test: i32) -> i32 {
        if buckets == 1 { return 0; }
        let rounds = minutes_to_test / minutes_to_die;
        let base = rounds + 1;
        let mut pigs = 1;
        let mut acc = base.clone();
        while acc < buckets {
            pigs += 1;
            acc *= base;  // or call .pow() each time
        }
        pigs
    }
}
```
A single round is a truth table; multiple rounds means more states per input.
If we have one round, we need `ceil(log2(buckets))` pigs (binary logic).
If we have two rounds, we need `ceil(log3(buckets))` pigs (trinary logic).
Pattern: R rounds means (R+1)-ary logic with logarithm base R+1.
As math:
<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/svg.image?pigs\geq\log_{R+1}(buckets)"/>
This is easier to compute as
<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/svg.image?(R+1)^{pigs}\geq{}buckets"/>
Since buckets <= 1000, pigs cannot exceed 10, so we might as well count up to it.
Also, zero pigs is only possible with one bucket; rest need >=1 pigs.

